




TY  - JOUR
T1  - Adaptive Forecasting Models Based on Predictive Distributions
AU  - Winkler, Robert L.
AU  - Smith, Wayne S.
AU  - Kulkarni, Ram B.
Y1  - 1978/06/01
PY  - 1978
DA  - 1978/06/01
N1  - doi: 10.1287/mnsc.24.10.977
DO  - 10.1287/mnsc.24.10.977
T2  - Management Science
JF  - Management Science
JO  - Management Science
SP  - 977
EP  - 986
VL  - 24
IS  - 10
PB  - INFORMS
N2  - The availability of data regarding variables of interest in forecasting problems is sometimes limited, but experts may possess a great deal of relevant information. The approach taken in this paper involves the development of adaptive forecasting models based on such information. Since the models and their parameters are difficult to consider intuitively, information from the experts is elicited in terms of predictive distributions of the variable to be forecasted. Various models can then be considered, and attempting to ?fit? a model to the predictive distributions is analogous to attempting to fit a model to a set of observations. This general approach to forecasting is developed in this paper, and a specific model, a linear model with normally distributed errors, is considered in some detail. An actual application involving the forecasting of fatigue life of asphalt pavements illustrates the development of forecasting models from experts predictive distributions.
AB  - The availability of data regarding variables of interest in forecasting problems is sometimes limited, but experts may possess a great deal of relevant information. The approach taken in this paper involves the development of adaptive forecasting models based on such information. Since the models and their parameters are difficult to consider intuitively, information from the experts is elicited in terms of predictive distributions of the variable to be forecasted. Various models can then be considered, and attempting to ?fit? a model to the predictive distributions is analogous to attempting to fit a model to a set of observations. This general approach to forecasting is developed in this paper, and a specific model, a linear model with normally distributed errors, is considered in some detail. An actual application involving the forecasting of fatigue life of asphalt pavements illustrates the development of forecasting models from experts predictive distributions.
